<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-078-908  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 078 908.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 22 1990 v24 n4 p129(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Training center do's and don'ts: it can provide the ideal learningenvironment, if given enough thought. (Training) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sebrell, William.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Corporate training centers can be excellent learning environments,but the specific features of the centers must be consideredcarefully ahead of time to assure they are conducive to learning.andO;A reception area should be included that is large enough to handlecoffee breaks and that provides a message center, severaltelephones and copying equipment.andP;  Restrooms should be largeenough to handle the number of people using them at break time,and a kitchen with a coffee maker and refrigerator for soda shouldbe included.andP;  Lockable cabinets should be provided in the storagearea for manuals, software, training handouts and spare equipment.andO;A technical training center should have workstations mounted underspecial desks with glass tops so as not to block students' views;there should be one workstation per student, and raised flooringand creative cabling should be considered.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     User TrainingTraining of EmployeesPlanningFacility ConstructionTutorialTechnical Instruction.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>